g.text: For SRP it would mean that a class is responsible for a specific task and the result of that task may be worked with by other entities. A class may not expose all it’s internals, because this would mean that the responsibility of its task could shift to other classes.

g.title: Folded Corner
g.desc: It is easier to ‘pin-point’ out what might be the functional ...

g.text: It is easier to ‘pin-point’ out what might be the functional affect of changing a class when it only performs a single responsibility, because code is more separated.

g.title: Folded Corner.56
g.desc: Multiple classes, all performing a single responsibility is m...

g.text: Multiple classes, all performing a single responsibility is much easier to understand in comparison to a monolithic, ‘god’ class performing all kinds of responsibilities.

g.title: Folded Corner.59
g.desc: A class containing multiple responsibilities, will have multi...

g.text: A class containing multiple responsibilities, will have multiple reasons to change. Adjusting one of these responsibilities may affect the others. Existing code may be affected accidently by the developer when there is ‘no clear’ separation of concern.

g.title: Folded Corner.62
g.desc: A developer is able to work more frequently with less interfe...

g.text: A developer is able to work more frequently with less interference of other developers, when a system is more distributed. This will result in less conflicts when using a version control system.

g.title: Folded Corner.65
g.desc: Modules which have a single responsibility and only one reaso...

g.text: Modules which have a single responsibility and only one reason to change can be re-used more frequently in other projects/parts of the system. This is because it more likely to perform a certain use-case then a monolith / ‘god’ - like module would.

g.title: Folded Corner.68
g.desc: Testing a unit which adheres to the single responsibility pri...

g.text: Testing a unit which adheres to the single responsibility principle will be easier and quicker to test because it has less uses-cases / functionality in comparison to an unit having multiple responsibilities. Testing our software easier and quicker means we can identify root cause of failures earlier and our problem ‘window’ is minimized to a single responsible unit.
